{"parse":{"title":"David Manning (fictitious writer)","pageid":973756,"revid":850685856,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>David Manning</b> (sometimes \"<b>Dave</b>\") was a pseudonym used by a marketing executive  around July 2000 to give consistently good reviews for releases from Sony subsidiary <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_Pictures\" title=\"Columbia Pictures\">Columbia Pictures</a>. Several fictional review quotes attributed to \"David Manning\" were used in the promotion of medieval action/drama <i><a href=\"/wiki/A_Knight%27s_Tale_(film)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"A Knight&#39;s Tale (film)\">A Knight's Tale</a></i> (describing <a href=\"/wiki/Heath_Ledger\" title=\"Heath Ledger\">Heath Ledger</a> as \"this year's hottest new star!\") and <a href=\"/wiki/Rob_Schneider\" title=\"Rob Schneider\">Rob Schneider</a>'s comedy <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Animal\" title=\"The Animal\">The Animal</a></i> (\"Another winner!\"),<sup id=\"cite_ref-Newsweek_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Newsweek-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> the latter of which generally received mixed to poor reviews by real critics.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Details\">Details</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=David_Manning_(fictitious_writer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Details\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Manning was named after a friend of Matthew Cramer, the Sony marketing executive responsible for the insertions. Manning was credited to <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Ridgefield_Press\" title=\"The Ridgefield Press\">The Ridgefield Press</a></i>, a small <a href=\"/wiki/Connecticut\" title=\"Connecticut\">Connecticut</a> weekly that actually published movie reviews written by the father-and-son team of Mark and Jonathan Schumann. During an investigation into Manning's quotes, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Newsweek\" title=\"Newsweek\">Newsweek</a></i> reporter John Horn discovered that the newspaper had never heard of him.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Newsweek_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Newsweek-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The story emerged at around the same time as an announcement that Sony had used employees posing as moviegoers in television commercials to praise <a href=\"/wiki/Mel_Gibson\" title=\"Mel Gibson\">Mel Gibson</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Patriot_(2000_film)\" title=\"The Patriot (2000 film)\">The Patriot</a></i>. These occurrences, in tandem, raised questions and controversy about ethics in <a href=\"/wiki/Movie_marketing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Movie marketing\">movie marketing</a> practices.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On June 10, 2001, on an episode of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Le_Show\" title=\"Le Show\">Le Show</a></i>, host <a href=\"/wiki/Harry_Shearer\" title=\"Harry Shearer\">Harry Shearer</a> conducted an in-studio interview with David Manning. The voice of Manning was provided by a computer <a href=\"/wiki/Voice_synthesizer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Voice synthesizer\">voice synthesizer</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-leShow20010610_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-leShow20010610-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On August 3, 2005, Sony made an out-of-court settlement and agreed to refund $5 each to dissatisfied customers who saw <i><a href=\"/wiki/Hollow_Man\" title=\"Hollow Man\">Hollow Man</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Animal\" title=\"The Animal\">The Animal</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Patriot_(2000_film)\" title=\"The Patriot (2000 film)\">The Patriot</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/A_Knight%27s_Tale\" title=\"A Knight&#39;s Tale\">A Knight's Tale</a></i>, or <i><a href=\"/wiki/Vertical_Limit\" title=\"Vertical Limit\">Vertical Limit</a></i> in American theatres, as a result of Manning's reviews.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=David_Manning_(fictitious_writer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Newsweek-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Newsweek_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Newsweek_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Horn, John (June 2, 2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20010609225327/http://www.msnbc.com/news/581770.asp?cp1=1\">\"The Reviewer Who Wasn't There\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Newsweek\" title=\"Newsweek\">Newsweek</a></i>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">McKittrick, Christopher (1 August 2016). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.thoughtco.com/sony-fake-film-critic-story-4062655\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>Did Sony Once Create a Fake Film Critic to Praise Its Movies?<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. <i>ThoughtCo.com</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">8 May</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=%22Did+Sony+Once+Create+a+Fake+Film+Critic+to+Praise+Its+Movies%3F%22&amp;rft.pub=%27%27ThoughtCo.com%27%27&amp;rft.date=2016-08-01&amp;rft.aulast=McKittrick&amp;rft.aufirst=Christopher&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thoughtco.com%2Fsony-fake-film-critic-story-4062655&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADavid+Manning+%28fictitious+writer%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-leShow20010610-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-leShow20010610_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Shearer, Harry (June 10, 2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20080530051629/http://media.harryshearer.com/?ProgramID=128\">\"le Show\"</a>. HarryShearer.com. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://media.harryshearer.com/?ProgramID=128\">the original</a> on May 30, 2008<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 5,</span> 2009</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=le+Show&amp;rft.pub=HarryShearer.com&amp;rft.date=2001-06-10&amp;rft.aulast=Shearer&amp;rft.aufirst=Harry&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fmedia.harryshearer.com%2F%3FProgramID%3D128&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADavid+Manning+%28fictitious+writer%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Elsworth, Catherine. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1495591/Sony-ordered-to-pay-1.5m-for-film-goer-hoax.html\">\"Sony ordered to pay $1.5m for film-goer hoax\"</a>. <i>The Telegraph</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">14 August</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Telegraph&amp;rft.atitle=Sony+ordered+to+pay+%241.5